Since the bacterial culture grows at a rate proportional to its size, we can say that &lt;math>\frac{dy}{dt} = ky&lt;/math>, where &lt;math>\displaystyle y(t)&lt;/math> is the number of bacteria at time &lt;math>\displaystyle t&lt;/math> (in hours).

The solution to this differential equation is:&lt;br>
&lt;math>
\displaystyle 
y(t) = y(0)e^{kt}
&lt;/math>&lt;br>&lt;br>

We are given that &lt;math>\displaystyle y(0) = 50&lt;/math> and &lt;math>\displaystyle y(1) = 250&lt;/math>, so we can solve for &lt;math>\displaystyle k&lt;/math> as follows:

&lt;math>
\begin{align}
y(1) &amp;= y(0)e^{k\cdot1}
\\ 250 &amp;= 50e^k
\\ 5 &amp;= e^k
\\ k &amp;= \ln5
\\
\\ \therefore y(t) &amp;= 50e^{\ln(5)t}
\\ &amp;= {\color{blue} 50 \cdot 5^t}
\end{align}
&lt;/math>
